<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_KernelSubSpace"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Kernel is a subspace</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>If <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> and <math>
               <latex>W</latex>
            </math> are subvector spaces of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math>, then the kernel of a linear map <math>
               <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
            </math> is a subspace of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math>. Moreover, if the <math>
               <latex>(m,n)</latex>
            </math>-matrix <math>
               <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
            </math> represents a linear map <math>
               <latex>T\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
            </math>, then <math>
               <latex>\Ker{T} = \NllSp{\Mtrx{A}}</latex>
            </math>
         </para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>To see that <math>
                  <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
               </math> is a subspace of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> observe the following</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math> is in <math>
                        <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
                     </math>
                     <subordinate>
                        <hot>because</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearTrafo0To0"/>
                           <info>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this theorem.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>
                     <math>
                        <latex>L(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> are in <math>
                        <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
                     </math>, then this means that</para.body>
               </para>
               <math.display>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0} = L(\Vect{y})</latex>
               </math.display>
               <para>
                  <para.body>But then</para.body>
               </para>
               <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>L(\Vect{x} + \Vect{y})</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=	</latex>
                        </math>
                        <companion>
                           <info>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use that <math>
                                       <latex>L</latex>
                                    </math> is linear and, hence, commutes with vector addition.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </companion>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>L(\Vect{x}) + L(\Vect{y})</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{0} + \Vect{0} = \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
               <para>
                  <para.body>This means that <math>
                        <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
                     </math> is closed under addition.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is in <math>
                        <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
                     </math>, then this means that <math>
                        <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>. Now, if <math>
                        <latex>t</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> is arbitrary, then</para.body>
               </para>
               <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>L(t\cdot \Vect{x})</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>t\cdot L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>t\cdot \Vect{0} = \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
               <para>
                  <para.body>This means that <math>
                        <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
                     </math> is closed under scalar multiplication.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ol>
         <para>
            <para.body>Thus <math>
                  <latex>\Ker{L}</latex>
               </math> is a subspace of <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>To see the second part of the proposition, recall that <math>
                  <latex>T(\Vect{x}) = \Mtrx{A}\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
               </math>, for all <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math>. But this means exactly that <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> belongs to <math>
                  <latex>\Ker{T}</latex>
               </math> if and only if <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\NllSp{\Mtrx{A}}</latex>
               </math>. â€“ The proof of the proposition is complete.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
